# pgauthz local configuration. Copy to `.env` and edit for your deployment:
#
#     cp .env.example .env
#
# docker compose reads `.env` automatically, and the helper scripts (env.sh,
# init.sh) source it too. The real `.env` is gitignored — keep secrets out of
# version control, and prefer a secret manager in real production. The defaults
# below reproduce the demo/dev stack, so an unset value is never a surprise.
#
# See docs/PRODUCTION.md for the full hardening checklist.

# ── Passwords (change ALL before production) ─────────────────────────────────
# Database superuser ('authz' role) — used by init.sh / admin connections.
PG_PASSWORD=authz

# Service login-role passwords. These are applied at FIRST DB init, so set them
# before the first `./init.sh`. To change them later, recreate the database:
#     docker compose down -v && ./init.sh
AUTHZ_AUTHENTICATOR_PASSWORD=authz   # PostgREST connects as this role
AUTHZEN_DIRECT_PASSWORD=authz        # AuthZEN-direct connects as this role

# ── JWT verification (OPA + AuthZEN) ─────────────────────────────────────────
JWT_ISSUER=https://auth.example.com
JWT_AUDIENCE=authz-api

# ── Write authorization (OPA fronts the writer) ──────────────────────────────
# The writer PostgREST no longer verifies JWTs itself — OPA is the single front
# door for reads AND writes. OPA verifies the token, then requires WRITER_ROLE
# within the JWT's roles claim, and forwards the write to the fixed-role writer.
# Match these two knobs to your issuer's claim shape (see docs/PRODUCTION.md):
#   JWT_ROLES_CLAIM — comma-separated dotted paths to roles arrays; roles are
#                     aggregated across all of them. Default "roles". Keycloak:
#                     "realm_access.roles,resource_access.authz-api.roles".
#   WRITER_ROLE     — role value that authorizes tuple writes (matched in any
#                     configured claim), default "authz_writer".
# JWT_ROLES_CLAIM=roles
# WRITER_ROLE=authz_writer
#
# Writer instance OPA forwards to. To run OPA READ-ONLY, leave this unset and
# don't deploy postgrest-writer; OPA's write rule then returns
# {"allowed": false, "error": "writes_disabled"}.
# POSTGREST_WRITER_URL=http://postgrest-writer:3001

# ── AuthZEN subject policy ───────────────────────────────────────────────────
# false = token-only (JWT subject authoritative; safe for user-facing APIs).
# true  = trusted PEP/PDP mode (request-body subject wins). The compose file
# defaults to false; the demo/test stack opts into true via env.sh. Leave this
# commented for the demo (env.sh handles it); set false explicitly in a
# production .env. (Setting it false here would make the AuthZEN tests fail,
# since they evaluate arbitrary body subjects.)
# ALLOW_SUBJECT_OVERRIDE=false

# ── Condition (ABAC) policy ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
# statement_timeout armed on the service roles. It bounds condition evaluation,
# but applies to EVERY query on those connections — size it above your slowest
# legitimate operation (time-travel, broad list_*).
CONDITION_STATEMENT_TIMEOUT=60s

# ── Contextual-tuple checks ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Contextual-tuple checks let the caller inject ephemeral tuples; the privilege
# is its own role (authz_contextual_reader), granted to no one by default. If
# set, init.sh GRANTs it to this role — use ONLY a trusted PDP/backend role.
# AUTHZ_CONTEXTUAL_READER_GRANTEE=my_trusted_backend

# ── Misc ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
DEFAULT_STORE=demo
# LOG_LEVEL=info
